segments.text: In the upgrading of the facilities, were you, in a sense, even though you're still in civil engineering, was it more of a logistics administration?
Or was it basically?
No, I'm still in design, construction, operation, and maintenance of facilities.
OK. OK.
The interesting question that you would ask, because shortly after I left the service,
they added to the staff called services, engineering and services.
And they put the mortuary, the commissary, the liquor stores, and everything else under this course of engineering.
Not having enough to do.
This was General Jones did that.
He made him engineering and services.
So he put all the services under him too.
I never experienced that.
They do now.
That sounds like a lot of responsibility.
At that time that I was at Wright-Patterson, I was regional vice president of the Society of American Military Engineers for the Ohio region.
The United States is divided into a number of regions.
So happens Texas is a region all by itself.
But I was a
and that comes up later on to support something else.
We had posts in Cincinnati and Philadelphia, one down in West Virginia, one in Columbus, one at Wright-Patterson, of course.
About six or eight posts in the region.
Now, is this outside of the military?
Yeah, this is a Society of American Military Engineers.
It's not government-funded, but it's made up of Army, Navy, Air Force, Marine, military, and civilian engineers that want to join.
Today, there are about 20,000 members in the Society.
Well, that's a good idea.
Well, why were you only there for a year?
Here's your last job then, Director of Facility Maintenance back in Washington with the Secretary of Defense.
Remember the name Sheridan?
Mr. Sheridan was on the board for the expansion of the Air Force Academy.
Mr. Sheridan was escorted to Comron Bay

sheridan was the top engineer in the department of defense and he made a request to the airport i have a vacancy for a director of facility maintenance and i want general huck johnson to fill the job and the department of defense asked the airport for somebody by name and the air force's policy that unless they had a real real strong objection
grant the Department of Defense the wish.
Mr. Sheridan asked for me by name and there wasn't a damn way I could get out of it.
I tried to not go.
Why?
I didn't want to go to the Department of Defense.
I didn't want to go back to the airport.
I mean back to Washington.
You get in the Department of Defense, you're gone from your service.
I was doing what I wanted to do.
I wanted to work in the airport.
And
But there wasn't a way I could do that.
That sounds like a lot of responsibility.
I'm surprised that it's not a two-star position.
You mean in the Department of Defense?
Yeah.
Well, at that time, the Air Force had only one two-star civil engineer.
And this was still guttered.
This was Riley, General Riley, Maurice Riley, Colorado.
He was the only two-star that we had in the Air Force.
Well, why is that?
Because the Army, the Chief of the Corps of Engineers, was three-star.
That's right.
Bear in mind, he has a greater responsibility.
The chief of the Corps of Engineers has a responsibility that, unless one of them has defined it for you, it's very difficult to understand.
He has two responsibilities.
He is responsible to the chief of staff of the Army for certain things.
And he is responsible to the Secretary of the Army without going through the Chief of Staff for other things.
The work that he does in civil work, the Chief of the Staff of the Army has absolutely no sales.
But that's only the Secretary of the Army being the titular advisor to the Chief of the Corps of Engineers.
There is, if you put it on a scale, there is a star difference.
The top Navy man in our business is a rear admiral upper half.
Unless you understand that off the tape, I'll tell you about that because I had nothing to do with it.
He's a senior two-star admiral.
Which is a two-star admiral.
Rear admiral, upper half.
Rear admiral, lower half, is a one-star.
No?
Rear admiral, lower half, in the time of peace.
When you look at it, you don't know whether he's upper or lower.
And sometimes, when I was in the Department of Defense, even, and I'd get into meetings, and a rear admiral would come in, and it was my job to say, upper or lower?
If he said lower, date of rank?
Because you've got to establish who is the senior.
Because what he's wearing, he could be, too.
But you have to look at him and say, up or lower?
He says, lower.
Data rank.
And then that tells you which one of you is the senior.
And that's your responsibility.
Well, when I was the director of facility maintenance, I had a rear admiral across the hall.
He had another directorate reporting.
He, too, reported to Mr. Sheridan.
But I outranked him.
But as we walked down the hall, he'd walk on the right because what he's wearing says he's a two-star, but he's not.
He's being paid as a one-star.
It's crazy.
Only in war do they drop back to the comic books.
Yeah, it was a big job.
I thoroughly enjoyed it.
I learned a lot.
I got a hell of a lot of exposure.
I already said I worked with the different services.
Some of the problems with my own were bigger than with the other, with the Army and the Navy.
Never had any problem with the Marines.
They're just damn thankful that somebody's trying to help them.
Oh, they are?
Oh, yeah.
The Marines, and I'm not knocking them, rightfully so, if you took a percentage of how many
of what percent of the total were available or committed to combat, you'd have a greater percent out of the Marines than you would out of any service.
And that's what I say.
When you get into that old operation and maintenance, logistical support, and design and construction, anybody that wants to help us, help us.
Because they just don't have the people there.
And, you know, that's the commandant's choosing, and he's going to put the max in.

And back to my own boss, when I was back there at Turner, he said, you can listen to your own people say that they want to have their own design and construction agents and push the core out of the building, but not while I'm here.
Because, number one, we don't have the manpower to devote to that
And number two, as long as the Corps of Engineers is responsible for it, if it goes wrong, we've got somebody else to blame.
And he said, but we don't have the manpower spaces to put into it.
It's all we can do to keep air crews.
Right.
Well, how are your relations with the Corps of Engineers?
Oh, mine, always great.
Really good.
Oh, yeah.
No problems.
I've never had problems.
No jealousies?
No.
Never.
And even to this day, I've got two major general friends that live right here in San Antonio, and the greatest people ever.
One of them was the number two man in the Corps, and the other one was the top engineer in the Ohio River Division when I was at Wright-Patt.
So in general, would you say that the Corps of Engineers
and the engineering groups, of course, of the Air Force and the Navy, do they work together fairly well?
Yeah.
You know, sometimes they're misunderstanding.
Sometimes the auditors have to get with each other and battle over dollars and stuff like that.
But I personally...
can see only one way of improving it, but it would never come about, and that would be to abolish it all, as the Canadians have done, and have only one agent, period.
Don't have Army principally, Navy in some parts of the world, and Air Force in England, or the United Kingdom.
Why won't they do that?
I think we've got other problems, you know, just nobody willing to tackle that one or else nobody wants to tackle it because the Corps is so involved also in civil work.
Sure, absolutely.
And of course there are people who think that now is just about the time that the Corps ought to invest itself in civil work because
You're beginning to see more and more articles in the technical pubs and even in the media of some of the breakdowns and the failures that have happened in the Corps and are now surfacing.
Now what were your responsibilities here then in your last job?
Principally policy making and budget review of the
budget review that is submitted by the four services.

Annually when they come in for their operation and maintenance appropriation, how much they would have budget for the operation of utilities and the maintenance of facilities and the same thing for housing and so on.
Of course, our review would
I don't know if it would come as any surprise.
We'd be constantly trying to get the service to raise that budget level.
Of course, every time you try to get them to raise it, well, it's got to come from somewhere else because somebody's got a ceiling on them.
But hey, man, that's not enough to keep these things from falling apart.
Come on, you've got to get more than that.
Let's get it up.
Let's get it up.
Let's get it up.
But it comes in in so many different elements and line items that it takes a hell of a long study to go through and then determine that,
Okay, you're probably marginal, or okay, and you're good, or so on.
But that's the budget we need.
And policy, oh, it can come in any different form.
For instance, during my tenure, Congress, in its wisdom, eliminated so many enlisted aides
As a general rule, a flag officer got an aide for each star.
Then Congress said, look how many enlisted people we've got.
They're doing nothing except waiting on generals and admirals.
Let's come out.
When I say in his wisdom, they didn't realize really who this hurt.
Because first you have to live in government quarters to have an aid.
If you live on the economy, you don't get an aid.
You have to live in government quarters.
So the guy out there on the economy, he didn't have one.
But now this guy that's living in government quarters, he cut out the aid.
And here's
This is a true estimate.
So then the servants come to you and say, hey, who's going to cut this guy's grass?
This brigadier general says, who's going to cut his grass?
Well, who's responsible for having the grass cut before the aid was lost?
Well, the aid is.
I said, I'm going to ask you the question again.
Who's responsible for having the grass cut
before that aid authorization is withdrawn?
Oh, the generalist.
I said, who is responsible for having the grass cut after the aid authorization is withdrawn?
Well, the generalist.
Then you've answered your question.
Oh, really?
You're telling us the general's going to cut the grass?
I said, no.
I phrased it.
Who is responsible for having the grass cut?
Now, if the general wants to go cut the grass, that's all right.
If he wants to have his son do it, all right.
If he wants to hire the kid across the street, or if he wants to hire this black guy that comes on base and cuts everybody's grass, that's all right.
Well, would you permit the general officer's landscaping to be included in the civil engineer's landscaping budget for the common grounds?
I said, do I look like a guy that's going to go over there on the Hill before Congress and say, yes, I was the one that authorized that?
I said, do you really think that I'm that much of a fool?
You know, you and me, this is all going on in 45 seconds.
But this is a three- or four-week dialogue of back and forth between services.
It all mellows down to this.
So the policy is, they'll handle it.
They wanted you to send men over to cut their grass.
Hard to let me raise, put it in the budget.
And the intent of Congress, take the aid away, and then I'm going to turn around and say, oh, but we'll spend the money some other way?
Not me, Dad.
I'll say not only I would not do it,
But if I find it in the budget, I know what your grounds are now.
And if I find it in there, my people will cut it off.
But, you know, these are real small things.
But before the committee of Congress, you could get a number of people crucified.
Sure.
Well, like I say, short conversation here, but this is three or four weeks of
four services, and then we also knew that they'd have maybe two or three meetings.
Well, now, look, we'll go over there tomorrow and talk to them like this, and y'all go over there the next day, and...
So what happened?
Did the generals have to find somebody?
The generals remained, like I said.
Who was responsible?
So they were responsible.
That's right.
They cut it themselves, or somebody did.
Or they hired somebody to do it.
Congress took their aid away.
Congress didn't tell you you had to go cut grass.
We were about to have you as a colonel living next door to me, and the civil engineer would come cut my grass, but tell you, Colonel, sorry, we can't cut your grass.
You're a colonel.
You know, what in the hell would that do?
Yeah, great for my own.
But, uh,
What other challenges?
Well, the good news part, of course, was there was an Army Corps of Engineers general, and you probably have him on your list, Andy Rollins.
Is Andy in Texas?
Have you interviewed him yet?
No, I have not.
I've written him a letter.
Andy was the number two man of the Corps of Engineers.
And I won't say much about it, because you probably won't.
And everybody thought Andy was going to be promoted to three stars as Major Chief of Engineers.
And is he here in San Antonio?
I don't think so, no.
We've looked him up, but I don't think so.
But you know him?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
I was wondering why he hasn't responded.
He was the Vice President of the Society of American Motor Engineers.
And the Vice President usually ascends to become the President the following year.
And when the announcement was made that General Gribble was going to be moved into the Corps and made the Chief, Andy says, I quit.
I've had enough time.
See, I can't get promoted.
And
turned to the society and said, I can't accept the position of president because it could interfere with my taking a real good position somewhere.
And so how, all of a sudden, they were without somebody to go in.
And this was just at the time that I moved into Washington.
So they came to me and said, look.
The society came to you?
Yeah.
I made it clear.
They came to me and said, look, you've been a reasonable vice president before.
becomes the president.
I said, well, I'll ask my boss and my wife, but not in that order.
He'd say, yes.
Yeah, I'll take it.
So he said, yes.
Boy, Sheridan was great.
He says, great.
Greatest thing that ever happened.
Good that we got somebody in the Department of Defense for a change.
It's always been in the Army, Air Force, or Navy, and now we got somebody in the Department of Defense.
He says, anytime you want to travel,
travel to be sure that while you're on that trip you do some business for the Department of Defense though.
Great.
Okay, good.
We did it.
So did you travel quite a bit?
Oh, yeah.
Did you give any talks?
Oh, yeah.
And the department gave you time off for this?
I sandwiched it in with work every time that I went somewhere.
had it pretty well planned two or three weeks in advance and always had something to do.
You see, the Army, I mean, the Department of Defense has a lot of agency of its own, you know, Defense Mapping Agency.
They've got agencies scattered everywhere that don't report to Army, Navy, Air Force, don't report to one of the three services.
They report right back to the Department of Defense.
Like they've got a place they lovingly call the Pants Factory in Philadelphia.
They manufacture uniforms for all the services.
Now, all of the uniforms are not manufactured there, but enough are that they know what to contract for and how much they ought to cost when they contract for them and so on.
And if they have a special uniform or something, it's manufactured in Philadelphia.
Well, that outfit reports back to the Department of Defense, not to one of
One time it's commanded by a two-star Air Force, next time by a two-star Army, and then by an Avro, it floats around.
But anyway, there was enough business to keep it.
So that was the plus mark.
I mean, it was great.
It was a real good thing.
Sheridan was outstanding in the support.
And when we had our annual meeting the year I was president, well, I thought it was held in Houston.
I was little.
I wanted it somewhere in Texas, and I figured Houston was a good place to have it.
Why'd you decide to retire in 1974?
I'll be very honest.
I had sat at my position in my position in the Department of Defense for two cycles, but it's two general officer promotion cycles.
And it didn't come to be, and I went down to talk

guy that i knew real well and he was the number two man in personnel business and i said god uh what do the tea leaves have and he says well he says i know you're disappointed that you didn't get quoted i said well i'd be foolish to say that i wasn't disappointed but i said john
I'm one grade higher than I ever expected to be, and I'm glad of it, but I'm wondering about the future.
And he said, well, you're going to stay at the Department of Defense one more year.
And I said, and then what?
He said, and then we'll bring you out and make the command civil engineer out of you.
In other words, give you your own command.
No, that's what I'd already been.
So I told him, I said...
A command is like SAC, Air Force Logistics Command.
I said, John, I've already been the command engineer of Air Force Europe, of the Air Force Logistics Command.
I said, what other carrot could you give me?
And he said, well, you could give me SAC.
I said, I don't think that's as big a carrot as a log command.
Well, you asked what the tea leaves said.
I said, well, at least you're honest with me.
If I want out now, what do you say?
I'd like to have six months.
And I said, all right.
You'd like to have six.
What if I give you five?
I can live with five.
Okay.
I said, but now before I walk out of here, I want to tell you something.
I said, I'm the third Air Force general that just sat in that job down there.
It's never been rotated to the Army or the Navy or the Marines.
They've hit the Air Force three in a row.
From the inside, I can't see that we're gaining a thing.
They've not given us a thing.
All they're doing is just robbing the Air Force of one general officer.
We don't get any more.
We don't get any more.
Beep up in an authorization, or you don't get one more because you're furnishing them.
It comes out of our heart is to have any gentlemen we can have, and we've furnished three in a row now.
That's over a period of eight years.
I said, next time I can tell them no.
All right.
Let me think about that.
So the next time did the job go?
When I left, I recommended to my Army full colonel,
be given the job.
As a very dear general.
No.
Jobs don't give you the promotion.
Promotions are work no matter what your job is.
You're given the job.
He was given the job.
He sat in that job two years.
He's still full colonel today.
And sure enough, he's here.
Department of Defense asked the Air Force, and the Air Force said, sorry, we don't have them.
We can't give you one this time.
They turned them down.
It didn't cost them a thing.
They just turned them down.
They haven't been hit, you know, their budgets haven't been cut.
They haven't been nasty.
I don't know why.
And I had talked to John a couple of times, you know, after that.
And he said, well, I took your advice, and we told them no.
I said, as a result, we've got one more gentleman in the Air Force.
He said, that's right.
It's an important job, but we were just losing the job.
Now, during that job, you were working with the Secretary of Defense quite a bit.
How'd you get along with him?
Well, he's far removed.
You've got to remember that the Secretary of Defense is a member of the Cabinet, and he's a member of the
and everything, and you really don't see him.
Of course, you feel him, but I've got the truth to say that in the capacity that he was in, I never saw him there.
Our illustrious governor of Texas was the guy that ran the Department of Defense.
How'd you get along with Clements?
He's all right.
I never did have to deal face to face with him because there were two people between me and him.

The job of operation and maintenance of facilities, though it's a damn important job as far as dollars are concerned, and what we have to use if we have to fight the manpower and weapons policies just occupy more of people's time and effort.
And I say that's the reason
That's the reason they have us experts do the other things.
And I'm serious.
They give you all the rope and say, man, you know, go.
Because, really, they're just too damn busy fighting.
Manufacturers, Douglas, Northrop, you know, they've got more to do.
I don't see how some of them ever make it with us.
Talk about people.
Sure, we can put in long hours, but ours are long and tedious.
But theirs are grueling and trying to keep from getting screwed.
Of course, during this time, Watergate was on everybody's mind in Washington, D.C., and I was wondering if Watergate and the resignation of Richard Nixon and
in 74, which was the same time that you retired, if that had any impact on the Pentagon, any feelings at the Pentagon or in your department?
Well, I don't think it had any.
on efficiency or anything like that.
But it was there, and there were a lot of people in the Department of Defense at the senior level that had been brought in by the Democratic Party years ago, even though they were civil servants.
For instance, this guy Sheridan asked for me by name that I worked for directly.
Openly criticized the Republicans all the time.
He was a Democrat.
And of course, being a military guy, I listened to him in New Orleans and whatever.
I thought it was right politically.
But I don't think it had any effect on efficiency.
Or should we go get something to eat?
Yeah.
As far as I can see, we're basically done with your career, unless you have other things that you'd like to talk about, and we can talk about those after lunch.
All right.
We'll talk a few minutes after lunch.
Maybe there's some things on your notes that you don't know.
Okay.
His name is Captain Harvey Lively.
L-I-V-E-L-Y.
Okay, he is the attack officer during the cavalry on tape number one, and we'll edit that in.
Yeah, okay.
Okay.
Also, you asked the question...

When I went with the A&M football team out to California to play UCLA, that was not the first time that I'd been out of Texas because that particular maneuver was just three or four months before that in the New Mexico.
Okay, so that was the first time that you'd been out of Texas.
We'll edit that in, too.
When you think back on your military career,
And I know that we've alluded to this, but we haven't answered this.
You said that the way that you were promoted was because of work.
Did you think that you had some control over your promotions?
I mean, in all advancement, it seems to me that there is a certain amount of luck and a certain amount that the individual accomplishes.
And I was wondering, as far as you're concerned, what's your opinion?
of which one is more important?
Between the two?
Being there at the right time or hard work?
Well, in the Air Force, since we do not have branches of service, all of what's known as the line of the Air Force compete with each other.

That means the pilot competes with the supply officer, who competes with the maintenance officer, who competes with the civil engineer, who competes with the adjutant or the administrative officer with the personnel.
Those are all the line of the Air Force.
And they compete against each other.
Doctors compete against doctors.
Chaplains against chaplains.
But the rest of us being line of the Air Force.
And so by...

use of the Central Promotion Board, which, incidentally, all meet at Randolph, and the boards having only records and written recommendations to look at, except in the time of war, and there is a difference, sure, performance is the key to promotion.
Because that's what you're graded on,
even if the grades are skewed high, the written word is there to back it up.
And if a board gets concerned that, man, for the last three years they've been going overboard and fireballing everybody, let's go back and see what the written word is.
Well, it takes them longer, but it's there to look at.
And so performance always in time of peace.
In time of war, in other words, if
Got to be in a position vacancy to get a promotion.
Well, certainly, it's being in the right place at the right time.
Now, you are in the civilian world in your own business, as a matter of fact, for half a dozen years.
Do you think that getting ahead, advancing in the military,
Are there differences or similarities between advancing and any other bureaucracy, like the corporate world, for example?
No.
Again, time of peace, no.
Did you consider yourself ambitious?
Yes.
Very much so.
Always discussing it.
There wasn't something to do.
Always looking for something.
We've got to do more.
We've got to do more with less.
This is especially true after I returned to duty, that I was trying to do it for less cost.
I don't care whether it's manpower measured in hours or positions or dollars or what, but do it cheaper.
As well and cheaper or better.
Being class-dependent.
Hmm?
Being class-dependent.
Cross-conscience always.
Back to, again, what General Metten said about the two of them.
These are the only two guys that ever met a payroll.
The only guys that ever realized that if it doesn't pay, it ain't worth it.
Somebody's got to pay for it.

And sometimes, politicians especially, will talk about all the waste there is in the Department of Defense, and if you really want to take a look at waste, let's take a look at the budget of the Department of Defense, blah, blah.
You've probably heard this ad nauseum.
And I was wondering what you thought about that.
Well, I'd like to look and see who those people are.
Because...
Which people?
That are saying that.
Who the people are that are saying that.
Because I am convinced that with the review and the ringer that the sub...

committee the military appropriation subcommittee of the house appropriation subcommittee the ringer that they put us through and the review and the records that they call for and the hours of testimony that we have convinced somebody that we're doing as good a management job as the state of the union will permit us to do now two years from now a year from now it might be different you know it might be

some knowns that we didn't know when we went before the committee but you know you've got a house appropriation committee that covers all of appropriations but the military appropriation the sub committee for military appropriation is the one that deals solely with the department of defense with all the branches with all the agencies and everything they have that committee has a staff
And the longer that staff deals with the services and the agencies, the more they know about them, the more they know what to ask for.
And I would just like for some of these other people to just sit in on some of the reviews and hearings before they sign them.
The Department of Defense is a big whipping boy.
Yeah.
I'd be the last one to say that there's not some kind of saving somewhere in the Department of Defense.
Anybody that says that bit, boom.
Have you ever heard the term, and this is often used by politicians or by journalists, have you ever heard the term military mentality?
I don't know that I have.
Well, that there's an army way to do something, you know, or... Well... People in the military have certain opinions.
That's synonymous with... That's close enough to the government essence.
Is there a military way of thinking?
I don't think so.
Not unless you're talking about somebody that's...
They just advise that they think that their service is the only one that can do something and that nobody else can do it.
I'm sure that at one time or another some Air Force, maybe even a gentleman, said, well, the Navy doesn't know how to fly fighter aircraft.
Well, they don't.
They fly them just as well in the Air Force.
They fly them under different conditions in different locations.
No, I don't think there's really a military way of thinking about it.

In your entire career, were there some shortcomings, some things that you wanted to accomplish that you thought were just, I mean, you tried, but they were out of your reach for a number of different reasons?
I don't think there were any major consequences when I was first assigned to the Pentagon.
You know, again, the Pentagon has got the quotations around it.
Coming out of England as chief of the master planning branch.
Actually, I wasn't in the Pentagon.
My boss was in the Pentagon.
My branch was on paper.
We were under the headquarters of the US Air Force.
But we were downtown on the Mall.
I was within two blocks of the Capitol.
And I knew good and well that to increase our efficiency, we belonged over there in the Pentagon, in that building.
Spending too many man hours with my people going back and forth on the bus to attend meetings or coordinate papers and things like that.
Whereas if we were in the Pentagon, we would have had as much as maybe two more man spaces.
We were just losing that much of time.
And it just beat the daylights out of me.
And I just couldn't live with it.
I wasn't having much luck from my own boss in trying to get in, so I went over his head.
He didn't know it, but I went around him and started working with his boss to see if there was some way we could get in.

I accepted the fact that we would go in with about half the space that an individual is normally authorized and that I personally wouldn't ask for any more space for six to eight months after we got in, but then started
trying to improve our lot, which is what we did.
We just actually moved into some of these six by eight foot offices that we were talking about earlier.
And then that was after I was there about a year, and I got them in.
And then about a year later, we got sufficient space for what we're authorizing.
A master planner has got to have a desk.
He's also got to have a drawing board.
He does a hell of a lot of work on the table.
I explained this to my people, and they were all for it, because they didn't like riding the buses any more than I like for them to be riding the buses.
But I'm talking about, I had working for me eight GS-14s, which was a hell of a lot of pay, you know, in that day and time, and even today.
put them riding a bus for a couple hours a day, and you just throw the money down the drain.
You sure are.
But that was probably...
But you accomplished that.
Huh?
You accomplished the move then to the Pentagon.
Oh, yeah, but it was frustrating the first year, you know, and then having to take substandard to get in, I wasn't satisfied.

thing that I was asked to do or any assignment that I was given that didn't have some degree of success.
